so the players know, be there at this time, kill the minions, get the reward.

239
00:12:57,477 --> 00:13:01,819
The response that this kind of interval of reward produces is like this.

240
00:13:01,819 --> 00:13:06,581
You show up at a set time, respond, and then you go away until that set time.

241
00:13:06,581 --> 00:13:10,783
It's used a lot in mobile games for timers and daily login bonuses,

242
00:13:10,783 --> 00:13:14,044
which is effectively trying to pace out people using the game

243
00:13:14,044 --> 00:13:15,885
and have them coming back at certain times.

244
00:13:18,135 --> 00:13:21,156
Variable ratio is probably the most famous of these.

245
00:13:21,156 --> 00:13:22,437
It's used a lot in gambling.

246
00:13:22,437 --> 00:13:25,139
It leads to reward chasing behavior.

247
00:13:25,139 --> 00:13:28,101
And it is where there's a variable number of responses

248
00:13:28,101 --> 00:13:29,862
until the reward shows up.

249
00:13:29,862 --> 00:13:30,822
So it's not 10.

250
00:13:30,822 --> 00:13:34,925
It might be 10 to 50, something within that range.

251
00:13:34,925 --> 00:13:38,126
And loot drops, like the loot crate system in Paragon,

252
00:13:38,126 --> 00:13:39,327
are example of this.

253
00:13:39,327 --> 00:13:40,928
And critical hits are an example of this,

254
00:13:40,928 --> 00:13:43,730
where you hit a certain amount of times and will do damage.

255
00:13:43,730 --> 00:13:46,692
And the response rate that that tends to get

256
00:13:46,732 --> 00:13:48,933
is high and relatively steady.

257
00:13:48,933 --> 00:13:53,675
The reason it's steady is because it's unsure

258
00:13:53,675 --> 00:13:55,656
when the next critical hits, they will come along.

259
00:13:55,656 --> 00:13:58,598
You want to keep on trying to maximize those critical hits.

260
00:13:58,598 --> 00:14:00,659
There's no like, I've already got it,

261
00:14:00,659 --> 00:14:02,640
and I know I have to work harder

262
00:14:02,640 --> 00:14:04,101
until the next one comes at a certain set point.

263
00:14:04,101 --> 00:14:09,724
The last is variable interval, or event-seeking behavior.

264
00:14:09,724 --> 00:14:12,606
An example of this I found is from Destiny

265
00:14:12,606 --> 00:14:14,307
with their public events.

266
00:14:15,469 --> 00:14:20,432
happen at certain times but around that certain time and may not happen every time.

267
00:14:20,432 --> 00:14:25,335
And it generally encourages people to move into an area and hang around because they don't know

268
00:14:25,335 --> 00:14:31,799
exactly when it's going to happen. And this kind of random world event is a little bit more if you

269
00:14:31,799 --> 00:14:37,583
want to drive people to a zone and then have them wait around for things. It gets a pretty good rate

270
00:14:37,583 --> 00:14:41,625
of responding because you're not sure when when the event's going to occur and people will stick around.

271
00:14:42,114 --> 00:14:46,956
Now of course this is just a diagram I've copied off data from textbooks.

272
00:14:46,956 --> 00:14:51,238
And in a real game, in a lot of cases, you'll be mixing all these schedules together.

273
00:14:51,238 --> 00:14:53,299
They'll be running over top of each other.

274
00:14:53,299 --> 00:14:56,620
But it's kind of interesting to pull them out one by one like this

275
00:14:56,620 --> 00:14:58,861
and look at their kind of fundamental characteristics.

276
00:14:58,861 --> 00:15:00,842
So moving on from those.

277
00:15:01,197 --> 00:15:03,979
We want to talk about reward timing and uncertainty.

278
00:15:03,979 --> 00:15:09,165
Ideally, rewards should come immediately for success mechanisms,

279
00:15:09,165 --> 00:15:11,067
progress mechanisms, and choice mechanisms.

280
00:15:11,067 --> 00:15:14,650
If I make a choice, if I'm succeeding or I'm progressing in your game,

281
00:15:14,650 --> 00:15:17,854
I should know about it straight away, and I should be rewarded straight away.

282
00:15:18,415 --> 00:15:23,280
Now this doesn't necessarily mean we can't have long-term rewards that we're aiming for,

283
00:15:23,280 --> 00:15:26,063
but people are generally not great at long-term rewards.

284
00:15:26,063 --> 00:15:29,326
There's the famous marshmallow test where you give a kid a marshmallow

285
00:15:29,326 --> 00:15:33,490
and say if you wait, I'll come back in a few minutes, you can have two marshmallows,

286
00:15:33,490 --> 00:15:37,094
and you leave the room and the kid just shoves the marshmallow in their face.

287
00:15:37,094 --> 00:15:42,299
And as adults we like to go, ha, children, but actually we're all pretty bad at that.

288
00:15:42,907 --> 00:15:46,169
So if you want people to work to a long-term goal, they need to know there's a long-term

289
00:15:46,169 --> 00:15:49,831
goal and you give short little feedback bursts on the way there.

290
00:15:49,831 --> 00:15:52,953
Progression bars or experience bars are a classic example of this.

291
00:15:52,953 --> 00:15:56,535
They're little bursts of feedback, little bursts of reward to let you know you're making

292
00:15:56,535 --> 00:15:57,675
progress towards a big thing.

293
00:16:00,057 --> 00:16:05,140
Now, I've been talking a lot about, I've just talked about things being immediate rewards.

294
00:16:05,140 --> 00:16:07,842
Of course you can also have unexpected rewards.

295
00:16:07,842 --> 00:16:11,304
And unexpected rewards can be very strongly motivating.

296
00:16:11,304 --> 00:16:15,687
So an example of that would be in a game like Portal 2, you unexpectedly work out a way

297
00:16:15,687 --> 00:16:16,928
to solve the solution.

298
00:16:16,928 --> 00:16:22,132
It feels very satisfying, it's not something you necessarily saw coming, and it can feel

299
00:16:22,132 --> 00:16:22,632
good, right?

300
00:16:22,632 --> 00:16:23,393
Surprise puppy.

301
00:16:28,325 --> 00:16:34,552
But the problem with unexpected rewards is if I, in six slides time, showed this puppy again,

302
00:16:34,552 --> 00:16:36,374
it probably would have less impact.

303
00:16:36,374 --> 00:16:39,177
And if I kept doing it, it would have even less impact.

304
00:16:39,177 --> 00:16:43,842
And even if I mixed up different puppies, you might start to expect the unexpected.

305
00:16:43,842 --> 00:16:48,788
So, unexpected rewards can be really valuable, but they're hard to pull off, and they're hard to pull off repeatedly.

306
00:16:50,753 --> 00:16:55,239
The next thing I want to talk about with feedback is game feel, the way it feels to play your game.

307
00:16:55,239 --> 00:16:57,842
And I want to argue to go back to this idea of intrinsic motivation,

308
00:16:57,842 --> 00:17:00,084
that this is the ultimate in intrinsic motivation.

309
00:17:00,823 --> 00:17:04,905
A lot of companies when they talk about intrinsic motivation will talk about a lot of goal structures

310
00:17:04,905 --> 00:17:07,026
and adding a bunch of stuff on top of the game.

311
00:17:07,026 --> 00:17:07,887
And that can work.

312
00:17:07,887 --> 00:17:13,169
But if you look at the games that are commonly cited, games like Destiny as having great

313
00:17:13,169 --> 00:17:17,392
intrinsic motivation, they're games that just feel satisfying to play.

314
00:17:17,392 --> 00:17:22,094
That the action of just moving a controller or a mouse feels impactful and immersive.

315
00:17:22,094 --> 00:17:27,957
So there's an example of this from Gears of War and it's the active reload mechanic, where

316
00:17:27,957 --> 00:17:30,058
it takes the simple action of just pressing a button.

317
00:17:30,781 --> 00:17:32,922
to reload and makes it into a mini game.

318
00:17:32,922 --> 00:17:40,388
You've got a nice little bit of feedback there, a chance to succeed more or to fail.

319
00:17:40,388 --> 00:17:43,930
Of course, rhythm games like Thumper

320
00:17:43,930 --> 00:17:47,993
heavily rely on having a good game feel in order to succeed because all you're

321
00:17:47,993 --> 00:17:50,675
doing in these games is pressing left, right, up, down

322
00:17:50,675 --> 00:17:52,516
and buttons and rhythm.

323
00:17:53,572 --> 00:18:06,289
It's not that complicated a thing to be doing, really, but by using the rhythmic design and the sounds and the ramping up the difficulty, they can create a very compelling game feel.

324
00:18:06,289 --> 00:18:10,574
It feels satisfying, it feels like it builds, it feels like you're doing an important thing.

325
00:18:13,863 --> 00:18:18,728
I already mentioned Destiny, but Destiny, the developers at Bungie, worked very hard

326
00:18:18,728 --> 00:18:23,073
on making the animations and everything like that feel just really satisfying to reach

327
00:18:23,073 --> 00:18:27,539
out and every action in the game makes it feel like it has impact, even though, say

328
00:18:27,539 --> 00:18:31,143
this melee attack, all you're really doing is pressing a bumper on a controller, but

329
00:18:31,143 --> 00:18:33,766
it feels like you're really reaching out there and hitting your enemies.

330
00:18:35,658 --> 00:18:39,400
And even a simple screen shake, even though it may not be to everyone's taste,

331
00:18:39,400 --> 00:18:43,522
makes this space marine in Space Marine feel like he has weight,

332
00:18:43,522 --> 00:18:46,884
even though all that's happening is pushing forward on a stick.

333
00:18:46,884 --> 00:18:48,685
Feels like he's physically in the world.

334
00:18:48,685 --> 00:18:52,447
This is something we've done in Paragon with several of our heroes,

335
00:18:52,447 --> 00:18:54,648
and I want to just give a brief example of that.

336
00:19:17,806 --> 00:19:22,187
Okay, of course it's exaggerated for the trailer, but Steel's this big android and you can feel

337
00:19:22,187 --> 00:19:27,108
the weight to his moves, the weight to simply moving with him and simply pressing the button

338
00:19:27,108 --> 00:19:31,969
makes it feel satisfying to play even outside of the other structures of the game.

339
00:19:31,969 --> 00:19:33,870
It's six slides by the way.

340
00:19:35,470 --> 00:19:37,351
Alright, moving on. The next thing is progression.

341
00:19:37,351 --> 00:19:42,233
Progression towards clear goals. This is kind of pretty easy stuff.

342
00:19:42,233 --> 00:19:44,613
Progression towards clear goals, whether those are internally set

343
00:19:44,613 --> 00:19:49,395
or externally set by the game, is rewarding and, of course, relies on feedback.

344
00:19:49,395 --> 00:19:53,316
I already mentioned having to give progression feedback for long-term goals.

345
00:19:54,278 --> 00:19:58,801
And typical examples of this would be, this is from Paragon, we have a bunch of things,

346
00:19:58,801 --> 00:20:04,384
weekly quests, your progression in game as you level up and get new abilities in Almoba,

347
00:20:04,384 --> 00:20:09,267
daily victory chests, living up your account progress, all of this is progression and to

348
00:20:09,267 --> 00:20:13,370
show to players that things are happening and that their actions are being rewarded.

349
00:20:14,660 --> 00:20:18,642
Progression is also commonly used in tutorials, or at least tutorials that do

350
00:20:18,642 --> 00:20:19,862
things well.

351
00:20:19,862 --> 00:20:22,443
This is the tutorial from Unreal Tournament.

352
00:20:22,443 --> 00:20:25,604
It's clearly telling the player what to do, to jump.

353
00:20:25,604 --> 00:20:29,166
It's showing a modeling character doing that action,

354
00:20:29,166 --> 00:20:33,587
and the player cannot progress out of that room without doing the action.

355
00:20:33,587 --> 00:20:35,448
They can't leave without jumping over that barrier.

356
00:20:35,448 --> 00:20:39,169
And once they do, they have immediate feedback that it was successful because

357
00:20:39,169 --> 00:20:39,870
they're out of the area.

358
00:20:40,844 --> 00:20:44,765
The interesting thing about the UT tutorial, which I think is a nice element to it, is

359
00:20:44,765 --> 00:20:47,806
it has optional skill tokens in it.

360
00:20:47,806 --> 00:20:53,127
Optional skill tokens are, as the game teaches you, there'll be skill tokens hidden around

361
00:20:53,127 --> 00:20:56,107
the tutorial that kind of build on what you've already learnt.

362
00:20:56,107 --> 00:21:00,708
So if you've learnt jumping and wall running, maybe in the next room, off in the corner

363
00:21:00,708 --> 00:21:05,009
it's not required for you to do, there's a token spinning up there that requires you

364
00:21:05,009 --> 00:21:06,310
to jump and wall run to get it.

365
00:21:06,817 --> 00:21:11,801
You don't have to do it, but it's a way for you to put together what you've previously learned and show your progression.

366
00:21:11,801 --> 00:21:18,628
So this will be an example. This is probably the hardest one in the tutorial. It's pretty difficult to get.

367
00:21:18,628 --> 00:21:22,751
You can't jump over there, so you need to scoop around,

368
00:21:22,751 --> 00:21:26,455
like slide up a wall, jump around and then slide out to get it.

369
00:21:26,455 --> 00:21:32,340
It's pretty difficult, but it's a nice way to show players progress that doesn't also make them feel forced.

370
00:21:34,125 --> 00:21:36,886
Progression can also be shown by a social comparison.

371
00:21:36,886 --> 00:21:40,868
This is the post game screen that was added to Dota 2

372
00:21:40,868 --> 00:21:44,390
a while ago, where it shows, after the game is over,

373
00:21:44,390 --> 00:21:46,771
the progression of each player during the match.

374
00:21:46,771 --> 00:21:49,733
And it lets the players look and rank themselves

375
00:21:49,733 --> 00:21:52,694
within this information and know how well they did

376
00:21:52,694 --> 00:21:55,336
at certain times over the match and hopefully learn from this

377
00:21:55,336 --> 00:21:56,436
or be rewarded by it.

378
00:21:57,324 --> 00:22:01,207
Now, comparison, especially to other players, can open the path to abuse.

379
00:22:01,207 --> 00:22:03,248
So often making it only available after a game,

380
00:22:03,248 --> 00:22:06,511
where players cannot interact with each other is a good idea.

381
00:22:06,511 --> 00:22:10,654
Hiding MMR is a good idea, so people don't attack each other for,

382
00:22:10,654 --> 00:22:13,036
you're on my team and you've got 200 less MMR than me,

383
00:22:13,036 --> 00:22:16,319
so I'm instantly going to think that you're worse off at playing the game,

384
00:22:16,319 --> 00:22:18,621
because your matchmaking rank's lower.

385
00:22:18,621 --> 00:22:20,762
And making stat tracking websites opt-in.

386
00:22:20,762 --> 00:22:23,084
So if you want to see how good I am at Dota

387
00:22:23,084 --> 00:22:24,986
by looking on a stat tracking website,

388
00:22:24,986 --> 00:22:26,627
you can't, because I haven't opted in.

389
00:22:29,107 --> 00:22:32,910
And what's actually been happening recently that's interesting in games is

390
00:22:32,910 --> 00:22:35,453
the idea of comparison within yourself.

391
00:22:35,453 --> 00:22:36,033
So in

392
00:22:36,033 --> 00:22:40,858
Overwatch, for example, at the end of the match, they don't compare you against the

393
00:22:40,858 --> 00:22:44,761
other players, they compare you against your own progression over the game.

394
00:22:44,761 --> 00:22:48,065
So even if you've lost the game, maybe you've got better at something, maybe that

395
00:22:48,065 --> 00:22:49,946
was your best ever game at healing.

396
00:22:50,747 --> 00:22:53,689
or your third best ever game at healing or whatever it might be.

397
00:22:53,689 --> 00:22:57,012
It's some kind of reward that lets you know that you're progressing yourself

398
00:22:57,012 --> 00:23:00,335
but is not potentially a negative comparison against other people.

399
00:23:00,335 --> 00:23:05,100
And Dota's similarly got this thing that shows you your average for the hero over certain metrics.

400
00:23:05,100 --> 00:23:09,844
Okay, so that's feedback. A lot of this other stuff is also feedback

401
00:23:09,844 --> 00:23:13,568
but I'll talk about it in a different way.

402
00:23:13,568 --> 00:23:15,049
Control and choice is important.

403
00:23:15,725 --> 00:23:19,027
So what we're talking about here is feeling in control.

404
00:23:19,027 --> 00:23:25,231
We like to feel like we have choice and control and generally speaking we just like feeling limited,

405
00:23:25,231 --> 00:23:26,952
controlled or out of control.

406
00:23:28,344 --> 00:23:31,725
And there is a slight difference between feeling controlled and feeling out of control.

407
00:23:31,725 --> 00:23:34,726
I hope that you can get, even though they're kind of the same thing.

408
00:23:34,726 --> 00:23:39,448
There's an exception to this, and that's unless we choose to be controlled and limited.

409
00:23:39,448 --> 00:23:44,170
If we choose to cut off paths for ourselves that are presented to us,

410
00:23:44,170 --> 00:23:47,311
making interesting, meaningful choices within the game,

411
00:23:47,311 --> 00:23:49,852
then that can make us feel in control as well.

412
00:23:49,852 --> 00:23:53,493
So the statement like, people don't like feel controlled,

413
00:23:53,493 --> 00:23:56,495
doesn't necessarily mean they don't like feeling limited.

414
00:23:56,955 --> 00:24:00,636
They just like feeling like they have choice in those limitations.

415
00:24:00,636 --> 00:24:03,336
So this is often talked about around story.

416
00:24:03,336 --> 00:24:07,097
And there's different approaches that can be taken here.

417
00:24:07,097 --> 00:24:08,817
You can go crazy like The Witcher 2,

418
00:24:08,817 --> 00:24:13,198
where a whole act of content can be skipped based on a decision by a player.

419
00:24:13,198 --> 00:24:17,900
They completely miss a massive chunk of hours and hours of content

420
00:24:17,900 --> 00:24:18,940
based on a choice.

421
00:24:18,940 --> 00:24:21,300
It makes choices feel very meaningful in the game.

422
00:24:22,807 --> 00:24:25,130
You can also look at performative stories,

423
00:24:25,130 --> 00:24:27,192
where there isn't actually much formal story,

424
00:24:27,192 --> 00:24:30,276
and there's not much choice in a game like Journey,

425
00:24:30,276 --> 00:24:32,198
except for the way that you play out the game

426
00:24:32,198 --> 00:24:35,703
and the way that the story is created around your character.

427
00:24:35,703 --> 00:24:38,546
And then you can look at maybe more traditional structures

428
00:24:38,546 --> 00:24:40,969
of story games, like the original Walking Dead.

429
00:24:41,724 --> 00:24:45,769
where they very successfully created a feeling of choice that was

430
00:24:45,769 --> 00:24:47,571
praised for its feeling of choice.

431
00:24:47,571 --> 00:24:49,894
Even though if you go back and play through the game and make different

432
00:24:49,894 --> 00:24:52,497
decisions you'll find out that actually the choice

433
00:24:52,497 --> 00:24:55,500
doesn't strongly matter to how the game plays out.

434
00:24:55,500 --> 00:25:00,085
There'll be different people that fill in at different times for people you let die

435
00:25:00,085 --> 00:25:01,127
or whatever might happen.

436
00:25:01,767 --> 00:25:06,191
but because it felt like you were making a decision at the time, it feels important.

437
00:25:06,191 --> 00:25:10,234
And this can be contrasted against Mass Effect 3, which came out the same year, and used

438
00:25:10,234 --> 00:25:15,758
a similar structure, but because players had expectations built up over two games beforehand,

439
00:25:15,758 --> 00:25:20,502
and maybe they were more likely to play through more often, players would know, oh, it doesn't

440
00:25:20,502 --> 00:25:25,306
really matter, this character shows up here anyway, and some players were disappointed

441
00:25:25,306 --> 00:25:25,626
by that.

442
00:25:26,287 --> 00:25:30,388
Now, that's not to say that this was fundamentally wrong, it's just I'm trying to make a point

443
00:25:30,388 --> 00:25:36,230
about player expectation about control and how it can be good, but it can also backfire.

444
00:25:36,230 --> 00:25:40,732
It also interacts with activities in progression.

445
00:25:40,732 --> 00:25:46,494
So what I'm talking about here is examples like side activities in open world games.

446
00:25:47,277 --> 00:25:52,479
If the side activities feel forced upon a player, or they feel like they have to do them in order to progress,

447
00:25:52,479 --> 00:25:58,162
or they're being bugged to do a side activity, they may resist doing it. It may feel like control.

448
00:25:58,162 --> 00:26:03,424
Escort quests can also be very controlling, because they're essentially taking away success from the player

449
00:26:03,424 --> 00:26:08,946
and putting it in the hands of the NPC they have to look after, that can get in trouble or die or break stealth.

450
00:26:09,126 --> 00:26:14,627
Modern escort quest type games like Last of Us solve this by making the person you're

451
00:26:14,627 --> 00:26:19,928
escorting not do these behaviors, so they can't break your cover or they can't die.

452
00:26:19,928 --> 00:26:24,289
This of course is a trade-off for immersion, but it's a worthwhile one for the player not

453
00:26:24,289 --> 00:26:26,429
feeling controlled and frustrated.

454
00:26:26,429 --> 00:26:28,470
And then the other one is of course grind.

455
00:26:28,470 --> 00:26:32,670
If players don't feel like the activities they're doing in a game have meaning, are

456
00:26:32,670 --> 00:26:35,211
showing progression, and are meaningful to them.

457
00:26:35,675 --> 00:26:42,919
then they're more likely to view having to make a lot of daggers to level up in Skyrim

458
00:26:42,919 --> 00:26:44,440
as a grinding activity.

459
00:26:46,829 --> 00:26:51,772
And in fact, this idea about control being so important has come up in the recent literature

460
00:26:51,772 --> 00:26:58,577
as a suggestion to replace intrinsic versus extrinsic and to talk about instead autonomous

461
00:26:58,577 --> 00:27:00,638
or controlled behavior.

462
00:27:00,638 --> 00:27:06,962
And internally motivated behavior, if you feel obligated to yourself, can feel controlling

463
00:27:06,962 --> 00:27:08,563
and be demotivating.

464
00:27:08,563 --> 00:27:14,567
Just like external behavior can feel autonomous if there's a lot of choices set up for you.

465
00:27:15,364 --> 00:27:19,531
So this idea of control seems to be a core point where a lot of theories are agreeing.

466
00:27:19,531 --> 00:27:24,901
And I've been saying it's perception of control that matters, and that is the important point.

467
00:27:24,901 --> 00:27:28,347
You can give players an illusion of control and get just as much...

468
00:27:29,383 --> 00:27:31,124
Impact is real control.

469
00:27:31,124 --> 00:27:34,666
So games like P.E.G.O. where you fire into a random zone, but because you pick where

470
00:27:34,666 --> 00:27:38,947
you fire and you have a special skill, can feel like you're more skilled than the game

471
00:27:38,947 --> 00:27:40,868
is actually working on.

472
00:27:40,868 --> 00:27:43,009
And of course match three games can be masters of this.

473
00:27:43,009 --> 00:27:47,591
You have no control over what's about to fall on the screen at all as a player, but because

474
00:27:47,591 --> 00:27:52,613
of the way that the feedback is presented to you, it feels like you made a really weighty

475
00:27:52,613 --> 00:27:56,015
important decision, even though you just like matched one line.

476
00:27:58,210 --> 00:28:02,853
The last, well, one of the last things about control is this interesting idea of counter-control

477
00:28:02,853 --> 00:28:05,494
that came out of behaviorism, it's been around for a while.

478
00:28:05,494 --> 00:28:09,616
And it's typically the idea that when people feel controlled, we often counter to this.

479
00:28:09,616 --> 00:28:12,397
And this is often talked about in a negative way.

480
00:28:12,397 --> 00:28:15,979
If people feel controlled in your game, they feel like it's grindy, they'll stop playing it.

481
00:28:15,979 --> 00:28:18,100
That's how they break the control of your game.

482
00:28:18,100 --> 00:28:19,761
They're like, no, stop, I'm out.

483
00:28:20,521 --> 00:28:25,566
However, it can actually be used as a game mechanic because it feels very rewarding to break control.

484
00:28:25,566 --> 00:28:28,129
So a classic example of this would be the Stanley Parable,

485
00:28:28,129 --> 00:28:34,115
which is a game all about a narrator trying to control you and your attempts to break that control.

486
00:28:34,115 --> 00:28:38,139
And it feels very satisfying to do so, even though you ultimately fail.

487
00:28:38,139 --> 00:28:41,523
So the last thing...

488
00:28:43,343 --> 00:28:45,525
is control and tutorials.

489
00:28:45,525 --> 00:28:48,246
Now, when a lot of people hear this stuff about control

490
00:28:48,246 --> 00:28:51,207
and feeling controlled is negative,

491
00:28:51,207 --> 00:28:53,148
they'll say, okay, we're not gonna put tutorials in

492
00:28:53,148 --> 00:28:54,529
or we're gonna do tutorials

493
00:28:54,529 --> 00:28:56,690
that have no controlling elements and no guidance in them

494
00:28:56,690 --> 00:28:59,451
because it's better for people to learn things.

495
00:28:59,451 --> 00:29:02,393
Now, that can work out, but the problem is

496
00:29:02,393 --> 00:29:05,894
it's feeling in control and not feeling out of control.

497
00:29:07,104 --> 00:29:11,959
Really, big ways to feel out of control is to feel confused and unclear and not know

498
00:29:11,959 --> 00:29:13,203
what the hell is going on.

499
00:29:14,167 --> 00:29:18,370
And so having a little bit of handholding, a little bit of guidance in tutorials,

500
00:29:18,370 --> 00:29:22,473
if it lets your players get to the point where they can feel in control,

501
00:29:22,473 --> 00:29:24,955
like you're telling them what to do and then suddenly they have control

502
00:29:24,955 --> 00:29:27,437
and they can show that control, it can be worth it.

503
00:29:27,437 --> 00:29:31,440
So this idea of control doesn't necessarily mean don't make tutorials.

504
00:29:31,440 --> 00:29:34,863
And of course, that's one of the nice things about the optional skill tokens

505
00:29:34,863 --> 00:29:37,845
in Unreal Tournament, is that there are optional things players can do

506
00:29:37,845 --> 00:29:41,128
to show that they've mastered the mechanics that you're teaching them.

507
00:29:43,402 --> 00:29:48,204
Okay, last thing in control is non-contingent rewards.

508
00:29:48,204 --> 00:29:50,305
These might be known as participation awards.

509
00:29:50,305 --> 00:29:54,467
Who thinks participation awards are a dumb idea?

510
00:29:54,467 --> 00:29:55,948
Not as many people as usual.

511
00:29:55,948 --> 00:30:01,250
Participation awards kind of came out of SDT and the intrinsic model theory.

512
00:30:03,328 --> 00:30:07,171
and there's a reason for that and it's that participation awards which are

513
00:30:07,171 --> 00:30:11,074
awards you get for just showing up are less likely to be seen as controlling

514
00:30:11,074 --> 00:30:15,077
which we've said is not good and more likely to be unexpected right because

515
00:30:15,077 --> 00:30:17,119
you don't have to do anything to get them they're not based on your

516
00:30:17,119 --> 00:30:19,961
performance of course because they're not based on your performance they're

517
00:30:19,961 --> 00:30:23,324
not really giving you feedback on anything however there are multiple

518
00:30:23,324 --> 00:30:27,427
occasions that they're used in video games so probably the one that the

519
00:30:27,427 --> 00:30:30,249
people have the most negative association with its rubber banding

520
00:30:30,862 --> 00:30:37,892
This was where mechanics in the game like in Mario Kart will help losers equalize with winners.

521
00:30:37,892 --> 00:30:41,718
And it's good for casual games because nobody wants to just be beaten over and over again

522
00:30:41,718 --> 00:30:44,001
if they're supposed to be just having fun with their kids or family.

523
00:30:45,316 --> 00:30:47,998
Another example from more hardcore games is gold drips in MOBAs.

524
00:30:47,998 --> 00:30:52,963
As long as you're playing a game of a MOBA, there's just some constant resource coming

525
00:30:52,963 --> 00:30:57,206
to you, no matter how well you're doing, that might let you buy that one item you needed

526
00:30:57,206 --> 00:31:01,730
to win the team fight and come back in a situation you were otherwise losing.

527
00:31:01,730 --> 00:31:05,413
A similar example in Titanfall 2 is the Titan drop.

528
00:31:06,960 --> 00:31:12,184
progression which like a gold drop in a MOBA was just constantly coming in in Titanfall 2.

529
00:31:12,184 --> 00:31:15,327
So even if you're getting beaten and not performing very well,

530
00:31:15,327 --> 00:31:18,710
you probably still got to use your Titan and experience that part of the game

531
00:31:18,710 --> 00:31:21,153
and get that reward during a match.

532
00:31:21,153 --> 00:31:26,758
So that's what these non-contingent rewards can be quite useful for is this kind of balance

533
00:31:26,758 --> 00:31:31,282
and making sure people experience more of your game.

534
00:31:31,282 --> 00:31:32,823
You're a really wonderful audience by the way.

535
00:31:35,718 --> 00:31:39,562
Okay, so I'm not going to do a bunch of slides about this one, in fact this is the ODee slide,

