00:40:50,595 --> 00:40:53,836
they of course expect to get more from it.

693
00:40:53,836 --> 00:40:56,378
So you need to make sure your economy is balanced

694
00:40:56,378 --> 00:40:59,800
to support the people who spend more in your game,

695
00:40:59,800 --> 00:41:02,061
or at least they feel like they're getting more value.

696
00:41:02,061 --> 00:41:03,722
And in fact, some games...

697
00:41:03,722 --> 00:41:07,024
So it's important to go back to this idea of feedback

698
00:41:07,024 --> 00:41:08,605
and making sure that everything's very clear

699
00:41:08,605 --> 00:41:11,526
and the value of buying things is very clear

700
00:41:11,526 --> 00:41:13,727
and the value of the things you can purchase with money

701
00:41:13,727 --> 00:41:14,368
is really clear.

702
00:41:15,269 --> 00:41:17,191
even before you make the purchase.

703
00:41:17,191 --> 00:41:20,835
But some games will also, once you make a certain level of purchase,

704
00:41:20,835 --> 00:41:23,778
they'll, without telling you, modify the odds

705
00:41:23,778 --> 00:41:27,021
of certain good things happening for a little while afterwards.

706
00:41:27,021 --> 00:41:31,005
So the game suddenly is more in your favor after you've spent

707
00:41:31,005 --> 00:41:31,806
perhaps a dark pattern.

708
00:41:33,482 --> 00:41:36,486
Another thing with this is after a string of bad luck,

709
00:41:36,486 --> 00:41:37,548
we expect the payout.

710
00:41:37,548 --> 00:41:39,571
This is what keeps people gambling.

711
00:41:39,571 --> 00:41:43,096
But it can be something that we can use in games

712
00:41:43,096 --> 00:41:45,380
to reinforce this expectation and make people feel

713
00:41:45,380 --> 00:41:47,463
like your game is fairer and more in line

714
00:41:47,463 --> 00:41:48,204
with what they want.

715
00:41:48,985 --> 00:41:52,849
So an example of this from Destiny would be the Vanguard bonus.

716
00:41:52,849 --> 00:41:59,554
In Destiny when you run strikes you get loot, random loot based on how you play through

717
00:41:59,554 --> 00:42:00,515
the strike, it just pops up.

718
00:42:00,515 --> 00:42:05,819
And the more strikes you run in a row, the higher your Vanguard bonus gets, which increases

719
00:42:05,819 --> 00:42:10,123
your chance to get better stuff, which meets this expectation of the more effort I put

720
00:42:10,123 --> 00:42:11,344
in, the more I get out.

721
00:42:12,648 --> 00:42:17,773
Another example of this is non-replacing randomness and variable loot rewards like a loot crate.

722
00:42:17,773 --> 00:42:23,397
Once you've got something out once, it's out, and that increases the odds of you getting things that you actually want out of it.

723
00:42:23,397 --> 00:42:29,483
And that feels better to players. It's more in line with what they expect for their increased effort and increased spend.

724
00:42:29,483 --> 00:42:32,425
You also need to make sure you set expectations.

725
00:42:32,425 --> 00:42:34,987
This is another Destiny example.

726
00:42:34,987 --> 00:42:38,090
When Destiny launched, they had the Engram system.

727
00:42:38,090 --> 00:42:40,732
The Engram system shows you...

728
00:42:41,902 --> 00:42:44,164
is kind of random loot you pick up in the world.

729
00:42:44,164 --> 00:42:49,227
And when it launched, the color of the engram was the highest possible reward you could get out of the engram.

730
00:42:49,227 --> 00:42:53,530
Which set the expectation, if I see this, it's got to be an exotic, which is really cool.

731
00:42:53,530 --> 00:42:57,793
But you could hand it in to the Cryptarch, and you'd get a common item out of it.

732
00:42:58,673 --> 00:43:03,459
And people didn't like that very much because it was against what they felt was being represented to them.

733
00:43:03,459 --> 00:43:07,685
So in my understanding what Bungie did is they didn't change the drop tables,

734
00:43:07,685 --> 00:43:10,568
they didn't change the loot or the underlying math of this.

735
00:43:10,568 --> 00:43:14,834
All they did is color the engrams at the lowest possible thing you can get out.

736
00:43:15,493 --> 00:43:19,875
So now you saw a blue ingram, you knew you were going to get at least a blue item out of it,

737
00:43:19,875 --> 00:43:22,277
but maybe you got a surprise and got an exotic.

738
00:43:22,277 --> 00:43:28,921
So it's important to be aware of what expectations you're setting up for your players with the reward systems.

739
00:43:28,921 --> 00:43:32,883
The final bias I want to talk about is the idea of loss aversion.

740
00:43:32,883 --> 00:43:37,966
This is simply state that players will often work harder to keep something they have

741
00:43:37,966 --> 00:43:40,027
than to get something they could gain.

742
00:43:40,027 --> 00:43:41,968
So maybe a complicated example of this could be...

743
00:43:42,942 --> 00:43:47,405
If you're designing a MOBA and you want people to attack towers,

744
00:43:47,405 --> 00:43:51,448
you want to encourage them to stop playing defensive and get out there and attack,

745
00:43:51,448 --> 00:43:55,831
one thing you could consider doing is lowering the hit points of enemy towers,

746
00:43:55,831 --> 00:43:57,632
making them easier to take down and attack.

747
00:43:57,632 --> 00:43:59,713
You can achieve your attack more easily.

748
00:43:59,713 --> 00:44:00,554
And that might work.

749
00:44:01,975 --> 00:44:06,338
Or, what might happen is people might work that out and they might start playing even

750
00:44:06,338 --> 00:44:11,182
more defensive because people view that tower as something that they own and they control.

751
00:44:11,182 --> 00:44:16,306
And even though now it's easier to go out and gain, it's also easier to lose and people

752
00:44:16,306 --> 00:44:19,488
will often work harder to keep something they have.

753
00:44:19,488 --> 00:44:24,252
Other examples from games will be continuous login bonuses where if you don't login every

754
00:44:24,252 --> 00:44:26,233
day you lose progression.

755
00:44:26,233 --> 00:44:27,214
Of course...

756
00:44:27,354 --> 00:44:32,177
That can be a very negative thing if you actually hit that not logging in on the day.

757
00:44:32,177 --> 00:44:36,940
So sometimes you can buy that progression back or sometimes games don't use a continuous login bonus.

758
00:44:36,940 --> 00:44:41,543
You just get an increasing bonus every time you open it rather than it being continuous.

759
00:44:41,543 --> 00:44:46,186
Consumables and durability. People often hoard things like potions and consumables.

760
00:44:46,186 --> 00:44:50,308
Because of this reason we don't like spending something that's going to go away.

761
00:44:50,308 --> 00:44:53,510
So you need to make sure that the base rate and the drop rate of these things

762
00:44:53,510 --> 00:44:54,431
is good enough that maybe...

763
00:44:54,811 --> 00:44:59,173
people will use it or you really demonstrate the value of doing so.

764
00:44:59,173 --> 00:45:02,734
And paying to continue is a classic example of this,

765
00:45:02,734 --> 00:45:05,375
you're paying to keep the progression that you have.

